It's unclear if Trump ever saw this twitter account, but he might be unsophisticated enough to actually believe it actually belongs to James Comey (Comey "friend" Benjamin Wittes sort-of backs it up). Either way, it does look like Trump thinks Comey is somehow associated with these leaks.

The leaks leading up to the January 27th dinner between Trump and Comey tell a lot. First, several potentially relevant events lead up to the dinner:

- Trump has blamed the leak of the dossier on the IC, and appears to think U.S. intelligence agencies are leaking information on the Russia investigation out of hostility toward him.

- The Trump administration denied coordinating Flynn's contacts with the Russian ambassador and claimed they were innocuous, but the circumstances surrounding the calls hint at criminality or wrongdoing by Trump.

- Comey assured Trump he was not under investigation and refused to confirm the Russia investigation, and Trump has acted friendly toward Comey after others called for his resignation.

- According to Comey, Trump had asked Comey to stay on during the January 6th briefing, before the calls for Comey to resign. Comey also assured Trump he was not under investigation during this briefing.

- Trump has not yet said publicly he intends to keep Comey on as FBI director. He told 60 minutes he wanted to speak with Comey after the election first.

- Meanwhile, Trump has been briefed that Wikileaks is affiliated with Russian intelligence, and Wikileaks has threatened to release Trump's tax returns.


One mystery about Trump's and Comey's accounts of the Jan 27 dinner is: why can't they agree on who initiated it?


