	Under normal circumstances, the revelation might have been unsurprising: Comey is less than four years into a 10-year term, and it is extremely rare for a president to remove an FBI director. But President Trump had notably declined to say whether he would keep the FBI director, telling “60 Minutes” in an interview after his election that he wanted to meet with Comey first. 


Assuming Trump is watching the media like a hawk as usual, Trump learns the following leading up to the dinner:


- Carol Lee, Devlin Barrett, and Shane Harris of The Wall Street Journal report on Jan 22 that multiple U.S. intelligence agencies are investigating Flynn's contacts with the Russian ambassador.

- Ellen Nakashima and Greg Miller of The Washington Post report on Jan 23 that the FBI found no wronging and Flynn is not under investigation.

- Matt Zapotosky, Ellen Nakashima, and Greg Miller of The Washington Post and Adam Goldman of the NY Times report on Jan 24 that Trump intends to keep Comey as FBI Director.


But Trump hasn't publicly confirmed he wants Comey as FBI director yet, and Comey has recently faced calls for his resignation. On top of that, Trump has reasons to believe the WSJ report that Flynn is under investigation is legitimate: for one, he probably directed Flynn's calls and knows their contents. And  Trump has said the Wall Street Journal and "financial media" are "much better, much more honest" than "the political media," and the Trump campaign had previously revoked The Washington Post's press credentials for "incredibly inaccurate coverage."

For a man who sees patterns and deals being made over the media (and perhaps fancies himself a mob boss), it wouldn't be too hard for Trump to interpret these Washington Post reports as an offer for a deal by Comey--essentially, keep me as FBI director and the investigation into you goes away. Trump would notice the conspicuous disconnected between the WaPo report and the WSJ report, and would certainly notice if the Washington Post learned that he accepted Comey as FBI director before he did. Trump might also have picked up that Flynn had been interviewed by the FBI within a few hours of Comey's January 24th "job offer."

Yates perhaps throws a wrench in this deal. Two days after the supposed Comey "offer," Yates warns Trump that Flynn is vulnerable to blackmail, then invites him to review the evidence underlying his conduct. But this would surely inconvenience any supposed deal to make Flynn's investigation "disappear," as the WaPo article enticed, as Trump would have a hard time pretending the investigation didn't exist with knowledge of both the investigation and the underlying evidence. Trump will later claim he was "surprised" by Yates warning, having "read various articles" that Flynn was "just doing his job."

Trump goes on to hastily create an alibi to fire Yates, his conspicuously unconstitutional travel ban, surprising Yates and everybody else with its roll-out and causing global chaos. Trump asks Comey if he's not under investigation, threatens to investigate the dossier then asks for his loyalty. Comey tells Trump he's not under investigation, and he'll get "honest loyalty." Comey keeps his job.


The same set of authors at the Washington Post will go on to leak some details of Flynn's misconduct, prompting Trump to fire Flynn and confront Comey. Trump will ask Comey to make public he's not under investigation, reminding him he's been "loyal" to Comey and that "we had that thing you know." Trump will complain that leaks from the intelligence community are affecting his ability to "make deals," perhaps referring to deals with Russia:


https://web.archive.org/web/20170412000123/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/fbi-obtained-fisa-warrant-to-monitor-former-trump-adviser-carter-page/2017/04/11/620192ea-1e0e-11e7-ad74-3a742a6e93a7_story.html
	FBI obtained FISA warrant to monitor former Trump adviser Carter Page
	By Ellen Nakashima, Devlin Barrett and Adam Entous
 	April 11 at 7:11 PM

	The FBI obtained a secret court order last summer to monitor the communications of an adviser to presidential candidate Donald Trump, part of an investigation into possible links between Russia and the campaign, law enforcement and other U.S. officials said.

	The FBI and the Justice Department obtained the warrant targeting Carter Page’s communications after convincing a Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court judge that there was probable cause to believe Page was acting as an agent of a foreign power, in this case Russia, according to the officials. 

	...Applications for FISA warrants, Comey said, are often thicker than his wrists, and that thickness represents all the work Justice Department attorneys and FBI agents have to do to convince a judge that such surveillance is appropriate in an investigation. 


http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/328590-trump-reinforces-turnaround-on-syria-and-russia
	Trump reinforces turnaround on Syria and Russia
	04/12/17

	Asked if he thought Russia knew of the sarin nerve gas attack that the U.S. and its allies have pinned on Syrian President Bashar Assad, whose government has been facing armed opposition in a yearslong civil war, Trump hedged.

	“I think it's certainly possible. I think it's probably unlikely,” he said. “I would like to think that they didn't know, but certainly they could have.”

	...Trump has been signaling a more aggressive and antagonistic approach to Syria and Russia, Assad’s primary backer, since the chemical attack — moving away from his campaign promises to forge better ties with Moscow and to avoid U.S. military interventions in the Middle East. 


http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-russia-tillerson-putin-idUSKBN17E11W
	Wed Apr 12, 2017

	Putin says U.S.-Russia ties worse since Trump took office

	Levels of trust between Moscow and Washington have deteriorated since U.S. President Donald Trump took office, Russian President Vladimir Putin said in an interview broadcast on Wednesday.

	Asked about relations since Trump became president, Putin said, according to a transcript of the interview released by the Kremlin: "One could say that the level of trust on a working level, especially on the military level, has not improved, but rather has deteriorated."

	Asked about accusations that Syria's government launched a chemical weapons attack in Idlib province, Putin said that Damascus had given up its chemical weapons stocks.


